ween Coitus and Commodification: Young West German Women and the Impact of the Pill -- tChapter 13 Boy Trouble: French Pedophiliac Discourse of the 1970s -- tChapter 14 “More than a dance hall, more a way of life”:1 Northern Soul, Masculinity and Working-class Culture in 1970s Britain -- tPart V Cultures, Countercultures, Subcultures -- tChapter 15 Utopia and Disillusion: Shattered Hopes of the Copenhagen Counterculture -- tChapter 16 Juvenile Left-wing Radicalism, Fringe Groups, and Anti-psychiatry in West Germany -- tChapter 17 The End of Certainties: Drug Consumption and Youth Delinquency in West Germany -- tSelect Bibliography -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the 1960s and 1970s, Western Europe's "Golden Age" (Eric Hobsbawm), a new youth consciousness emerged, which gave this period its distinctive character. Offering rich and new material, this volume moves beyond the easy conflation of youth culture and "Americanization" and instead sets out to show, for the first time, how international developments fused with national traditions to produce specific youth cultures that became the leading trendsetters of emergent post-industrial Western societies. It presents a multi-faceted portrait of European youth cultures, colored by differences in gender, class, and education, and points out the tension between emerging consumerism and growing politicisation, succinctly expressed by Jean-Luc Godard in his 1967 pairing of "Marx and Coca-Cola."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aPopular culturezEurope. 0aSocial changezEurope. 0aSubculturezEurope. 0aYoung consumerszEurope. 0aYouthxPolitical activityzEurope. 0aYouthzEurope. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh1 aBourg, Julian, e